In Antwarp 26 Aprill
gend e Lury Hugh lay
in answer to yd of the 10: curitt am sorry, that yd aque doth still hinder
yd bussynes, besires the abstaeles yd cltheer maker to deliver thered
whoever send forward, what is ready for mee not doubting, butt you
will aggree with him, when he comes to towne, if I have butt a small
assortement of them as Desired shall desist, till he be better inclijned
to keep his word intrim I heare no more of the 6N silver mach
pack whites, of which I wrott you formerly, pray lett mee have so
much faveur from you that you provide 5 peeces p very first
for I have undertaken to deliver them to have them that are our
Jesuits, wherefore I hope you will prevaile with the maker to have
them that are pure goodand as cheap as the markett will offordson
which I do depend, whilst I wish you health & remainer
26 Aprill 1681
London Pickering & Ropbinson
messr. I have before mee yd of 11: curitt where by observe what is past atto
the desired goods from the north, all which is well, when yd freind there doth
make up the packes, you please to order him to make a pastarne boock
of each bale & send itt to ma with the invoyces, because as I noted heree
before weesell often goods bj the pattarnes before arrivall
you accept for yd acctt. the bale of tykes N. 14 which is noted accordingly
&yd remise send for acceptance, & when payd shall be noted myd creditt
for £117„5„5 without rebate: butt you do complaine that the
2 seales & greatleadare less then the sire as to that wee can nott
contradict, then those that are sworen sealers, do seale them
you say that great lead & 3 seale are to deare in proportion
that is because they cost so much more in makeing of each son
besides they are better fabrig I assure you every sort sold here currantly
as I note them free aboard: now to compleat the 130„ peeces shall
pick out the best sort goods & endeavour to make amends, for the worst
sort is worth the price here as I have noted, wherefore in case you an
not be incorridged by them, I am confident non will m. Collier
hat & drawne on mee for you in 2 bills £130:7 aprill which by
a ni stake he makes feb. so that I have sent the bil lach to Iam
& desired that should be made Apill beeng ready to aceept & pay itt
& yo remaine in exspectation to know what past in thenort
London Henry Collier
Antwarp 216 aprill 1681
th
S. my last to you was on the 19: curitt to which please to be reserred sence
Rec: yd of 11: ditto, as to the cloathes returned, I hope the loss will not
be so vreat, as doubt less itt should be by keeping them longer, therewas
never no mode so soone don as the yallow cullours, which keept them
all Backwards, I shall endeavour all I can to putt off the rest, hav g
told 3 this week, so there is not many lest & I have not yett hadd any
restants except itt be of yeallow culloure, as there is aboutt 12 a 15 p more
which are sent in to mee for acctt. of mr. slaughter, beeng to secure
him of P from Brussels, & I beleave to bre sent back also he haveng
advised to sell them for the north countrey trade which made as resolue
to what as don, butt pray keep this onely for yds governo
I have desired mr. Herrijnee to ddo the utmost to see if any thing yett
were to be had from T.H. I am sensible of yd misfortunes, prnipally
to what yd ere brought by yd goodness: whoever wee must have patient
with what is passed the frift curitt you have drawne on mee £130st
in 2 buls h first of februars insteed of Aprill, so have desired that, that
might bealtered, & that I shall pay itt att due day, which is the needfull
In Antwarpe 2 Aprill
att present with kinde saluts from
London Abram vivian
th
Sr. mij last to you was on the 23: curitt, sence receaved yd of 11 ditto where by
I understand what endeavours you are readdy to do to promote our conceones
in the northren trade sothen I shall leave the further execution on yd side to
you in all respects, onely heastely recommand you please to order, that as
soone any packes are compleated that the be sent to hull with all exspedition
princippally the bayes, for wee want goods here, good goods sell best & seeng
m Th. potter was in an amorous tins when he provided the bale N. 29„
so hope he will do well now priccipally itt now being the very best time
of all the yeare for buying, where fore lett espetiall care betaken that
wee be not backward & do endeavour that our cloathes may be of afull
lize & lett the lenghts go as itt will, all the bales well assorded, vrapied
with 3 or 4 white bayes & sent to hull as formerly, the coones the better
for I supose that vowards August wee shall have agreat demand &
I haveing few or no goods on ham, shall easely finde sale for y. as soore
as they come wherst fore pray be not bachward, the 28: curitt I have to
pay £500. for yd acctt. & then I'll proceed to remitt you as firstas
I can here is an engish yacht now aft ancher cap fasebie which
I supose will saile in 3or 4 dayes, I am a makeing of a packett of lace
N14 to send with him which will be the last that cormes from the
worck women till I have further orders from you whilst I remainee
26 Aprill 1681
London George Cole
th
Sr. my last to you was on the 19 curitt sence non from you, this then
cheefbij for covert to the inclosed bill for £64:10 att the charges of m.
Roussell att mijlord mul grave att white hall of 21t curitt 2 uso for
accompt of the estate of JS att 35„6 which please to hose accordingly
& so remaine wat kinde salut
